## Mark Speer's Chord Move in Detail (Key Teachable Technique)

His most described and distinctive technique: **take a jazz chord voicing on the top three strings and slide it chromatically or diatonically up and down the neck.** Example:

Take Cmin7add9 shape (say, played at the 8th fret on strings 1-2-3): move it up to the 4th position (becomes a different chord color), down to the 3rd, down to the 2nd. Because the bass player holds the root, these sliding upper-voice shapes create a constantly shifting harmonic texture without ever "resolving" in a traditional cadence. He calls this "sampling a wicked chord and moving it around like house music."

This approach is borrowed from vibraphone and piano jazz vocabulary (Roy Ayers, Herbie Hancock) where the upper voices of a chord are treated as independent melodic material.

