**Guitar approach:** Aguirre picked up electric guitar at 18. Given his influences (Santana especially), expect pentatonic-heavy lead work with extended modal passages — Dorian mode for the Latin-blues-meets-psych sound, Phrygian for Middle Eastern flavor. The cumbia rhythmic influence means syncopated 16th-note strum patterns rather than straight 8th-note surf rhythm.

**Gear:** Balthvs.com gear page returned 404, so no confirmed pedalboard. Given their KEXP sessions (audible from recordings), the tone is clean-to-slightly-driven with heavy reverb and likely delay for the psychedelic swirl. No heavy fuzz — their sound stays cleaner and more percussive than Mystic Braves.

**Specific technique:** The cumbia influence creates a "clave-based" feel even on rock songs — the guitar often plays shorter, stabbed chord hits rather than sustained strums, creating space for the rhythm section.

