### Bombino vs. Tinariwen: The Actual Differences

| Feature | Tinariwen | Bombino |
|---|---|---|
| Geography | Mali | Niger (Agadez) |
| Guitar lineage | Ibrahim Ag Oumarou → self-taught fire-circle tradition | Haja Bebe as mentor, supplemented by Hendrix/Santana video study |
| Tunings | DADGAD + multiple Tuareg open tunings | Open tunings + influences from British folk (Davy Graham) |
| Style | Droning, repetitive, minimal chord changes, trance-focused | More soloistic, rock-inflected, "Sultan of Shred" — actual lead guitar improvisation |
| Niger guitar character | Faster tempo, up to 4 chord changes (complex by Tuareg standards), alt tuning G-B-D-G-B-E | Oscillates between insistent riffing and quick-fire runs |
| Western influences | Early Jimi Hendrix cassettes, Ali Farka Touré | Hendrix, Santana, Dire Straits — studied more deliberately |
| Arrangements | Two-guitar drone + melody, vocal-group feel | More Western band format, added keyboards and lap steel |
| Sonic character | Rattling low tension, drone-first | Fluid improvisation, more guitar-forward in mix |

**Key insight**: Bombino uses "unlikely chord sequences" compared to Tinariwen — he introduces chord movement where traditional Tuareg style would sustain a drone. His training under Haja Bebe was systematic, not the oral fire-circle transmission.

